  "text": "The prometheus/prometheus repository enforces TLS and authentication for remote write endpoints through a multi-layered validation and configuration system.\n\n**Configuration Validation (config/config.go):**\n- The RemoteWriteConfig struct (line 1419) defines the configuration for remote write endpoints, including HTTPClientConfig which handles TLS configuration through the embedded config.HTTPClientConfig type from prometheus/common.\n- The validateAuthConfigs function (line 1491) enforces that at most one of the following authentication methods can be configured: basic_auth, authorization, oauth2, sigv4, azuread, or google_iam. This prevents conflicting authentication configurations.\n- The validateHeaders function (line 1529) validates that the authorization header cannot be set directly and must instead be configured via the dedicated authentication parameters (basic_auth, authorization, oauth2, sigv4, azuread, or google_iam).\n- RemoteWriteConfig includes fields for SigV4Config, AzureADConfig, and GoogleIAMConfig to support cloud-native authentication mechanisms.\n\n**Client Creation and Configuration (storage/remote/client.go):**\n- The ClientConfig struct (line 128) wraps HTTPClientConfig from prometheus/common and includes fields for various authentication mechanisms (SigV4Config, AzureADConfig, GoogleIAMConfig).\n- NewWriteClient function (line 183) creates HTTP clients with TLS configuration from HTTPClientConfig and applies authentication round trippers for SigV4, Azure AD, and Google IAM.\n- The function calls config_util.NewClientFromConfig which validates and applies TLS settings from the HTTPClientConfig.\n\n**Remote Write Storage (storage/remote/write.go):**\n- The ApplyConfig method (line 139) of WriteStorage creates new write clients for each remote write configuration, passing through all authentication and TLS settings.\n- Each RemoteWriteConfig is validated during unmarshaling, ensuring TLS and authentication configurations are correct before client creation.\n\n**Authentication Round Trippers:**\n- storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go implements Azure AD authentication:\n  - The AzureADConfig struct includes Validate() method (line 131) that validates Azure-specific configuration including cloud selection and authentication method choices (managed identity, workload identity, OAuth, or SDK).\n  - NewAzureADRoundTripper function (line 237) creates an HTTP round tripper that adds Bearer token authentication to requests (line 265).\n  - Multiple authentication credential types are supported: ManagedIdentity, WorkloadIdentity, OAuth, and SDK default credentials.\n\n- storage/remote/googleiam/googleiam.go implements Google Cloud authentication:\n  - The Config struct defines credentials file path for Google Cloud authentication.\n  - NewRoundTripper function (line 34) creates a round tripper that attaches Google Cloud access tokens to remote write requests using either a credentials file or default credentials.\n\n**Bearer Token Handling:**\nBoth Azure AD and Google IAM implementations use HTTP round trippers to inject Bearer tokens into the Authorization header of requests. The authorization header cannot be manually set in the headers configuration—it must be managed exclusively through the dedicated authentication configuration parameters, ensuring secure and consistent token management.\n\n**TLS Configuration:**\nTLS configuration is handled through the HTTPClientConfig (from prometheus/common) embedded in both RemoteWriteConfig and RemoteReadConfig. This configuration supports certificate files, key files, CA files, and TLS version enforcement, validated during the UnmarshalYAML process of RemoteWriteConfig (line 1473)."
}

